    "body": "### Problem\n\nI'm finding I can't use `nvim -d` with process substitution on MacOS. \n\nMy use case for this is to preprocess html with `xmllint --format --html` to get the tree that an html parser would generate. For testing purposes, something like `seq` should suffice.\n\n<details open>\n<summary>seq example</summary>\n\n```bash\n:; nvim --clean -d <( seq 1 10 ) <( seq 0 9 )\n```\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>xmllint example</summary>\n\n```bash\n:; nvim --clean -d <(\n    xmllint --format --html a.html\n  ) <(\n    xmllint --format --html b.html\n  )\n```\n</details>\n\nRunning either of these on my mac gives me two empty panes for /dev/fd/63 and /dev/fd/62, with the message `\"/dev/fd/62\" [Permission Denied]`.\n\n<img width=\"1006\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/8739d505-77b9-455f-9d90-39e85d519759\" />\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```bash\n:; nvim --clean -d <( seq 1 10 ) <( seq 0 9 )\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nBuffers are opened from process substitution command line arguments (`/dev/fd/63` `/dev/fd/62`).\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.10.4 Build type: Release LuaJIT 2.1.1736781742\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.1.754\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nMacOS 15.2\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm 20241129-152148-4906789a\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nhomebrew",
